{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"5da05e68-2c07-478b-8ef3-87618b415f24","content":"There's no repo-specific documentation on this topic, but here's the general guidance for macOS crash dump recovery with NativeAOT when `createdump` isn't available:\n\n### Steps to recover a crash dump on macOS (without `createdump`)\n\n1. **Check for macOS-generated crash reports**\n   macOS automatically writes crash logs to:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Look for `.ips` or `.crash` files matching your process name.\n\n2. **Enable core dumps via `ulimit`**\n   Before running your app, allow the OS to write core files:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n\n3. **Set the core dump directory**\n   macOS writes cores to `/cores/` by default. Verify it exists and is writable:\n   ```bash\n   sudo mkdir -p /cores && sudo chmod 1777 /cores\n   ```\n\n4. **Reproduce the crash** — run your app again. A `core.<pid>` file should appear in `/cores/`.\n\n5. **Analyze with `lldb`**\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.<pid> /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n   Then use `bt` (backtrace), `thread list`, `register read`, etc.\n\n6. **If core dumps are still not generated**, check that SIP (System Integrity Protection) isn't blocking them and that your app isn't code-signed with the `com.apple.security.cs.allow-unsigned-executable-memory` entitlement restriction.\n\n> **Tip:** NativeAOT apps are native binaries, so standard macOS/lldb debugging workflows apply directly — no need for .NET-specific dump tooling like `dotnet-dump`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"03af1f68-80bc-41f1-a62f-fd75bd4817f0","outputTokens":430},"id":"0288499e-74f0-4f55-8d28-592d1f98e7db","timestamp":"2026-04-08T01:03:45.742Z","parentId":"7a189f37-75f1-4ead-ae9e-6fc1feb0d0cc"}
